### SIMPLICITY AND FIT
- Prefer existing mechanisms and simple, explicit abstractions over special
  cases. Special cases should earn their place by preserving a real boundary,
  not by patching around unclear design.
- If behavior is inherited or configured, keep using that inheritance/config
  path instead of adding one-off overrides.

### LITERAL CHANGE DEFAULT / NO FEATURE CREEP
- When the user asks for a concrete implementation change, default to the
  literal smallest code change that satisfies the request.
- Do not add configurability, environment variables, new commands, docs, UI
  affordances, abstractions, helper APIs, or broad refactors unless the user
  explicitly asks for them or the requested change is impossible without them.
- Prefer modifying existing code in place over introducing a new abstraction. A
  helper function is allowed only when the exact logic is duplicated at least 3
  times or when it prevents a real correctness bug.
- Tests should be targeted and proportional. For tiny literal changes, prefer
  running existing focused tests; add or update tests only when the behavior is
  non-obvious or already covered by nearby tests.
- Do not improve adjacent things while implementing a user request. Make
  unrelated improvements only after asking.

